<TITLE> The nation mourns </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 28 (bdnews24.com) - The nation was mourning the officers and civilians slain in the BDR mutiny with flags flying at half mast on Saturday. The bloody 33-hour mutiny by rebellious border guards that began Wednesday left a death toll of 77 up to Saturday afternoon, though more than 70 officers were still reported 'missing'. Flags were at half mast at Bangabhaban, the prime minister's office, secretariat, all government offices and Bangladesh missions abroad. Special prayers were offered for the dead on Friday, during Jumma prayers, in all cantonment mosques across the cantonment, and at Baitul Mukarram National Mosque. Teachers, lawyers, and businessmen have expressed condolences for those killed in the BDR mutiny and their families. Attorney general Mahbubey Alam and additional attorney general M. Enayetur Rahman gave a statement of deep sympathy for the bereaved families on Saturday. Some 501 teachers of Dhaka University signed a statement of mourning for the dead in the tragic incident. They also lauded the prime minister in her handling of the crisis. The Federation of Bangladesh Chambers of Commerce and Industries, alongside 10 business organisations, expressed shock over the incident and condolences to the families of the dead. They demanded exemplary punishment of those who were behind the BDR mutiny, in astatement signed by Annisul Huq, president of FBCCI, and presidents of 10 other organisations. bdnews24.com/
